{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1774534178,"nonce":"W6gGHBXNMczICYHFvxHgV5o/yXE=","message":"**Status update 2026-03-26**\n\nSingle-adversary minimax training confirmed to produce 0.00% SISU velocity effect at batch 1499 (see previous comment for full diagnostics). The adversary converges to broad constant forces saturating force_max; controller adapts without using SISU.\n\n---\n\n**Approaches to try (Tier 1, in order):**\n\n**A. Control cost ratio tuning with minimax**\nCurrent minimax has loss_update disabled. Previous standard-training experiments showed velocity differences across pert_std only with ratio enabled. Minimax + ratio might produce different dynamics. Try ratios 0.2, 0.3, 0.5. Always both single and population-based adversary.\n\n**B. Multiplicative SISU gating**\nReplace additive SISU input with h * (1 + alpha * SISU) per-unit modulation. Mimics neuromodulatory gain control. Directly implements the gain modulation H-infinity predicts. Small code change.\n\n**C. Vanilla RNN (no gating)**\nRemoves the GRU update gate shortcut that lets the network ignore SISU. Diagnostic: if vanilla RNN shows SISU effect where GRU does not, confirms gating-laziness hypothesis.\n\nAll experiments run both single-adversary and population-based (K=5).\n\n---\n\n**Key theoretical framing:**\nThe GRU appears to learn a single unconditionally robust policy, ignoring SISU because the update gate can simply not integrate the SISU input. Velocity differences DO appear across pert_std (perturbation-trained models reach faster) but NOT across SISU values — the network collapses modal policies. Approaches A-C attack this from different angles: A (loss landscape), B (input pathway), C (architecture).\n\n---\n\n**Previously tried and failed:**\nRunning cost, CVaR, APT (6 variants), control cost ratio sweep (standard training), single-adversary minimax. See earlier comments and compaction summary for details.","files":null}]}